# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: time-translation-symmetry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The **12-hour clock** is a time convention in which the 24 hours of the day are divided into two periods: **a.m.** (from Latin ***ante meridiem***, translating to "before midday") and **p.m.** (from Latin ***post meridiem***, translating to "after midday").
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock has been developed since the second millennium BC and reached its modern form in the 16th century.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour time convention is common in several English-speaking nations and former British colonies, as well as a few other countries.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In English-speaking countries: "12 p.m." usually indicates noon, while "12 a.m." means midnight, but the reverse convention has also been used (see § Confusion at noon and midnight).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The natural day-and-night division of a calendar day forms the fundamental basis as to why each day is split into two cycles.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Originally there were two cycles: one cycle which could be tracked by the position of the Sun (day), followed by one cycle which could be tracked by the Moon and stars (night).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] This eventually evolved into the two 12-hour periods which are used today, one called "a.m." starting at midnight and another called "p.m." starting at noon.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock can be traced back as far as Mesopotamia and ancient Egypt.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Both an Egyptian sundial for daytime use and an Egyptian water clock for night-time use were found in the tomb of Pharaoh Amenhotep I.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] 1500 BC, these clocks divided their respective times of use into 12 hours each.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The ancient Romans also used a 12-hour clock: daylight and nighttime were each divided into 12 equal intervals (of varying duration according to the season).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The nighttime hours were grouped into four *watches* (*vigiliae*).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The first mechanical clocks in the 14th century, if they had dials at all, showed all 24 hours using the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by astronomers' familiarity with the astrolabe and sundial and by their desire to model the Earth's apparent motion around the Sun.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In Northern Europe these dials generally used the 12-hour numbering scheme in Roman numerals but showed both *a.m.* and *p.m.* periods in sequence.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] This is known as the double-XII system and can be seen on many surviving clock faces, such as those at Wells and Exeter.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Elsewhere in Europe, numbering was more likely to be based on the 24-hour system (I to XXIV).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock was used throughout the British Empire.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] During the 15th and 16th centuries, the 12-hour analog dial and time system gradually became established as standard throughout Northern Europe for general public use.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The 24-hour analog dial was reserved for more specialized applications, such as astronomical clocks and chronometers.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Most analog clocks and watches today use the 12-hour dial, on which the shorter hour hand rotates once every 12 hours and twice in one day.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Some analog clock dials have an inner ring of numbers along with the standard 1-to-12 numbered ring.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The number 12 is paired either with a 00 or a 24, while the numbers 1 through 11 are paired with the numbers 13 through 23, respectively.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] This modification allows the clock to also be read in 24-hour notation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] This kind of 12-hour clock can be found in countries where the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Even in those countries where the 12-hour clock is predominant, there are frequently contexts (such as science, medicine, the military or transport) in which the 24-hour clock is preferred.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In most countries, however, the 24-hour clock is the standard system used, especially in writing.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Some nations in Europe and Latin America use a combination of the two, preferring the 12-hour system in colloquial speech but using the 24-hour system in written form and in formal contexts.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The 12-hour clock in speech often uses phrases such as*... in the morning*,*... in the afternoon*,*... in the evening*, and *... at night*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] *Rider's British Merlin* almanac for 1795 and a similar almanac for 1773 published in London used them.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Other than in English-speaking countries and some Spanish-speaking countries, the terms *a.m.* and *p.m.* are seldom used and often unknown.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In most countries, computers by default show the time in 24-hour notation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Most operating systems, including Microsoft Windows and Unix-like systems such as Linux and macOS, activate the 12-hour notation by default for a limited number of language and region settings.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] This behaviour can be changed by the user, such as with the Windows operating system's "Region and Language" settings.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The Latin abbreviations *a.m.* and *p.m.* (often written "am" and "pm", "AM" and "PM", or "A.M." and "P.M.") are used in English (and Spanish).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] When abbreviations and phrases are omitted, one may rely on sentence context and societal norms to reduce ambiguity.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] For example, if one commutes to work at "9:00", 9:00 a.m. may be implied, but if a social dance is scheduled to begin at "9:00", it may begin at 9:00 p.m.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The terms "a.m." and "p.m." are abbreviations of the Latin *ante meridiem* (before midday) and *post meridiem* (after midday).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Depending on the style guide referenced, the abbreviations "a.m." and "p.m." are variously written in small capitals ("am" and "pm"), uppercase letters without a period ("AM" and "PM"), uppercase letters with periods, or lowercase letters ("am" and "pm" or "a.m." and "p.m.").
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Some style guides suggest the use of a space between the number and the a.m. or p.m. abbreviation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Style guides recommend not using a.m. and p.m. without a time preceding it.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The hour/minute separator varies between countries: some use a colon, others use a period (full stop), and still others use the letter h.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] (In some usages, particularly "military time", of the 24-hour clock, there is no separator between hours and minutes.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In speaking, it is common to round the time to the nearest five minutes and/or express the time as the past (or to) the closest hour; for example, "five past five" (5:05).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Minutes *past* the hour means those minutes are added to the hour; "ten past five" means 5:10.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Minutes *to, till* and *of* the hour mean those minutes are subtracted; "ten of five", "ten till five", and "ten to five" all mean 4:50.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Fifteen minutes is often called a *quarter hour*, and thirty minutes is often known as a *half hour*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] For example, 5:15 can be phrased "(a) quarter past five" or "five-fifteen"; 5:30 can be "half past five", "five-thirty" or simply "half five".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] The time 8:45 may be spoken as "eight forty-five" or "(a) quarter to nine".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Polish, rounding off is mandatory when using (spoken) 12-hour clock, but disallowed when using 24 hour notation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] 15:12 might be pronounced as "quarter past three" or "fifteen-twelve", but *not* "three-twelve" or "quarter past fifteen".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In older English, it was common for the number 25 to be expressed as "five-and-twenty".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In this way the time 8:35 might have been phrased as "five-and-twenty to 9", although this styling fell out of fashion in the later part of the 1900s and is now rarely used.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Instead of meaning 5:30, the "half five" expression is sometimes used to mean 4:30, or "halfway to five", especially for regions such as the American Midwest and other areas that have been particularly influenced by German culture.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] This meaning follows the pattern choices of many Germanic and Slavic languages, including Serbo-Croatian, Dutch, Danish, Russian, Norwegian, and Swedish, as well as Hungarian, Finnish, and the languages of the Baltic States.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Moreover, in situations where the relevant hour is obvious or has been recently mentioned, a speaker might omit the hour and just say "quarter to (the hour)", "half past" or "ten till" to avoid an elaborate sentence in informal conversations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] These forms are often commonly used in television and radio broadcasts that cover multiple time zones at one-hour intervals.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Minutes may be expressed as an exact number of minutes past the hour specifying the time of day (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is "six thirty-two").
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Additionally, when expressing the time using the "past (after)" or "to (before)" formula, it is conventional to choose the number of minutes below 30 (e.g., 6:32 p.m. is conventionally "twenty-eight minutes to seven" rather than "thirty-two minutes past six").
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In spoken English, full hours are often represented by the numbered hour followed by *o'clock* (10:00 as *ten o'clock*, 2:00 as *two o'clock*).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] This may be followed by the "a.m." or "p.m." designator, though some phrases such as *in the morning, in the afternoon, in the evening,* or *at night* more commonly follow analog-style terms such as *o'clock, half past three,* and *quarter to four.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] O'clock* itself may be omitted, telling a time as *four a.m.* or *four p.m.* Minutes ":01" to ":09" are usually pronounced as *oh one* to *oh nine* (*nought* or *zero* can also be used instead of *oh*).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Minutes ":10" to ":59" are pronounced as their usual number-words.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] For instance, 6:02 a.m. can be pronounced *six oh two a.m.* whereas 6:32 a.m. could be told as *six thirty-two a.m.*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] It is not always clear what times "12:00 a.m." and "12:00 p.m." denote.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] In Latin, **ante meridiem** (a.m.) means "before midday" and **post meridiem** (p.m.) means "after midday".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Since noon is neither before nor after itself, the terms a.m. and p.m. do not apply.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Although noon could be denoted "12 m.", this is seldom done and also does not resolve the question of how to indicate midnight.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] By convention, "12 a.m." denotes midnight and "12 p.m." denotes noon.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] However, many style guides recommend against using either because of the potential for confusion.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Many recommend instead using the unambiguous terms "12 noon" and "12 midnight", or simply "noon" and "midnight".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] These include *The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language*, *The Canadian Press Stylebook*, and the NIST's "Frequently asked questions (FAQ)" web page.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Alternatively, some recommend referring to one minute before or after 12:00, especially when referring to midnight (for example, "11:59 p.m." or "12:01 a.m.").
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] These include the UK's National Physical Laboratory "FAQ-Time" web page.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] That has become common in the United States in legal contracts and for airplane, bus, or train schedules, though some schedules use other conventions.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Occasionally, when trains run at regular intervals, the pattern may be broken at midnight by displacing the midnight departure one or more minutes, such as to 11:59 p.m. or 12:01 a.m.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Some authors have been known to use the reverse of the normal convention.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Richards in his book *Mapping Time* (1999) provided a diagram in which 12 a.m. means noon and 12 p.m. means midnight.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/12-hour-clock] Historically, the style manual of the United States Government Printing Office used 12 a.m. for noon and 12 p.m. for midnight, though this was reversed in its 2008 editions.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] The **180th meridian** or **antimeridian** is the meridian 180° both east and west of the prime meridian in a geographical coordinate system.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] The longitude at this line can be given as either east or west.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] On Earth, the prime and 180th meridians form a great ellipse that divides the planet into the Western and Eastern Hemispheres.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] The antimeridian passes mostly through the open waters of the Pacific Ocean but also runs across land in Russia, Fiji, and Antarctica.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] An important function of this meridian is its use as the basis for the International Date Line, which snakes around national borders to maintain date consistency within the territories of Russia, the United States, Kiribati, Fiji and New Zealand.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] The only places where roads cross this meridian are in Fiji and Russia.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] Fiji has several such roads and some buildings very close to it.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] Russia has three roads in the Chukotka Autonomous Okrug.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] Many geographic software libraries or data formats project the world to a rectangle; very often this rectangle is split exactly at the 180th meridian.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/180th-meridian] This often makes it non-trivial to do simple tasks (like representing an area, or a line) over the 180th meridian.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Clocks and watches with a **24-hour analog dial** have an hour hand that makes one complete revolution—360°—in a full day, or 24 hours per revolution.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In contrast, the more familiar 12-hour analog dial has an hour hand that completes two revolutions per day, or 12 hours per revolution.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Twenty-four-hour analog clocks and watches are commonly used by logistics workers, firefighters, police officers, paramedics, nurses, pilots, scientists, and military personnel.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] They are often preferred because they present an unambiguous representation of the entire day at once.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] This definition specifically refers to the use of a full circular dial to represent a 24-hour cycle.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Simply using numbers from 0 to 23 (or 1 to 24) is known as the *24-hour clock system*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials also use 24-hour analog dials, as the shadow follows a path that repeats approximately once per day.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many sundials are marked with the double-XII (or double-12) system, where the numbers I to XII (or 1 to 12) appear twice—once for the morning and once for the afternoon and evening.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Thus, VI (6) appears twice on many sundial dials: once near sunrise and once near sunset.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Modern 24-hour analog dials—aside from sundials—are almost always marked with 24 numbers or hour markers around the edge, following the 24-hour clock system.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Because they display the entire day in one rotation, they do not require AM or PM indicators.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] The ancient Egyptians divided the day into 24 hours.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] There are diagrams of circles divided into 24 sections in the astronomical ceiling in the tomb of Senemut.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sundials use some or all of the 24-hour dial, because they show the position of the sun in the sky.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Sometimes, for aesthetic rather than practical reasons, all the 24 hour marks are shown.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Medieval clocks often used the 24-hour analog dial, influenced by the widespread example of the astrolabe.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Northern Europe, the double-XII system was preferred: two sets of the Roman numerals I to XII were used, one on the left side for the night and morning hours, and another set on the right side of the dial to represent the afternoon and evening hours.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Italy, the numbers from 1 to 24 (I to XXIV in Roman numerals) were used, leading to the widespread use of the 24-hour system in that country.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] On Italian clocks, though, the I was often shown at the right side of the dial, rather than the top.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] This probably reflects the influence of the Italian timekeeping system, which started counting the hours of the day at sunset or twilight.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In northern Europe, the double-XII system was gradually superseded during the 14th and 15th centuries by the single-XII (12-hour system), leading to the widespread adoption of the 12-hour dial for popular use.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 24-hour analog dial continued to be used, but primarily by technicians, astronomers, scientists, and clockmakers.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] John Harrison, Thomas Tompion, and Mudge built a number of clocks with 24-hour analog dials, particularly when building astronomical and nautical instruments.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour dials were also used on sidereal clocks.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] The famous Big Ben clock in London has a 24-hour dial as part of the mechanism, although it is not visible from the outside.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Astronauts used the 24-hour format due to the lack of day/night in the space environment.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 20th century, the 24-hour analog dial was adopted by radio amateurs, media, pilots, maritime, submariners, government, diplomats and for military use.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] 24-hour analog watches and clocks are still being manufactured today, and are sought after by collectors and enthusiasts.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Manufacturers who make 24-hour analog watches include Glycine, Raketa, Vostok, Fortis, Poljot, Swatch, and many others.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] A few rare variants place noon and midnight at the right and left sides.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] There is no ambiguity if the 24-hour numbering is used.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the United States, the government and military commonly use 24-hour clocks having noon at the bottom; the variant with noon at the top is far less common.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Multiple time zones can be displayed by having multiple hour hands or a rotating bezel.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel is a ring around the outside of the watch's face.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] When it is used, the top of the watch always represents midnight (or noon) GMT.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] The bezel, which also has hour markings, is then rotated so that its numbering represents local time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] So, a pilot always has GMT time available for talking to air traffic control and, when they land, only has to rotate the bezel to "set" the watch to their new local time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Glycine was the first to feature a 24-hour rotating bezel in 1953 with the Airman No.1 pilot watch.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] The design became widely known when Rolex designed the Rolex GMT Master for Pan-Am pilots in 1954.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] A 24-hour watch with a compass card dial can be used to determine direction when set to local noon and used in conjunction with the Sun.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Many (but not all) digital watches can be set to show the time in 24-hour format.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] A common use for the 24-hour analog method of representing time is for showing the way the time of day depends on one's location.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] George Orwell uses the 12-hour and 24-hour dials to symbolize the old and new worlds in his novel *Nineteen Eighty-Four*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] The 12-hour dial is a relic of pre-revolutionary society, used to represent the desirable past; the 24-hour dial and time system is the compulsory standard imposed by the Party, and represents both conformity and the undesirable nature of the new world.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] It was a bright cold day in April, and the clocks were striking thirteen.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In the 1927 film *Metropolis*, the opening scene shows both a 24-hour analog clock and a 10-hour (decimal) analog clock, one above the other.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] Both are used to convey the impression of an alien and highly efficient society.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] In Jules Verne's 1870 science fiction masterpiece *Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas*, Captain Nemo remarks that the clocks in the *Nautilus* use a 24-hour dial: "Now, look at that clock: it's electric, it runs with an accuracy rivaling the finest chronometers.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] I've had it divided into twenty–four hours like Italian clocks, since neither day nor night, sun nor moon, exist for me, but only this artificial light that I import into the depths of the seas!
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-analogue-dial] A watch with a 24-hour analog dial is important to the resolution of Alfred Bester's 1953 short story "The Roller Coaster".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The modern **24-hour clock** is the convention of timekeeping in which the day runs from midnight to midnight and is divided into 24 hours.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] This is indicated by the hours (and minutes) passed since midnight, from 00(:00) to 23(:59), with 24(:00) as an option to indicate the end of the day.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] This system, as opposed to the 12-hour clock, is the most commonly used time notation in the world today, and is used by the international standard ISO 8601.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] A number of countries, particularly English speaking, use the 12-hour clock, or a mixture of the 24- and 12-hour time systems.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In countries where the 12-hour clock is dominant, some professions prefer to use the 24-hour clock.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] For example, in the practice of medicine, the 24-hour clock is generally used in documentation of care as it prevents any ambiguity as to when events occurred in a patient's medical history.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] To indicate the exact end of the day, hh may take the value 24, with mm and ss taking the value 00.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In the case of a leap second, the value of ss may extend to 60.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] A leading zero is added for numbers under 10, but it is optional for the hours.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The leading zero is very commonly used in computer applications, and always used when a specification requires it (for example, ISO 8601).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Where subsecond resolution is required, the seconds can be a decimal fraction; that is, the fractional part follows a decimal dot or comma, as in 01:23:45.678.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The most commonly used separator symbol between hours, minutes and seconds is the colon, which is also the symbol used in ISO 8601.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In the past, some European countries used the dot on the line as a separator, but most national standards on time notation have since then been changed to the international standard colon.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In some contexts (including some computer protocols and military time), no separator is used and times are written as, for example, "2359".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In the 24-hour time notation, the day begins at midnight, 00:00 or 0:00, and the last minute of the day begins at 23:59.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In the ISO 8601 notation, 24:00 may also be used to refer to midnight at the end of a given date — that is, 24:00 of one day is the same time as 00:00 of the following day.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The notation 24:00 mainly serves to refer to the exact end of a day in a time interval.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] A typical usage is giving opening hours ending at midnight (e.g.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Similarly, some bus and train timetables show 00:00 as departure time and 24:00 as arrival time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Legal contracts often run from the start date at 00:00 until the end date at 24:00.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] While the 24-hour notation unambiguously distinguishes between midnight at the start (00:00) and end (24:00) of any given date, there is no commonly accepted distinction among users of the 12-hour notation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Style guides and military communication regulations in some English-speaking countries discourage the use of 24:00 even in the 24-hour notation, and recommend reporting times near midnight as 23:59 or 00:01 instead.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Sometimes the use of 00:00 is also avoided.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In variance with this, an older version of the correspondence manual for the United States Navy and United States Marine Corps specified 0001 to 2400.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The manual was updated in June 2015 to use 0000 to 2359.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Time-of-day notations beyond 24:00 (such as 24:01 or 25:00 instead of 00:01 or 01:00) are not commonly used and not covered by the relevant standards.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] However, they have been used occasionally in some special contexts in the United Kingdom, France, Spain, Canada, Japan, South Korea, Hong Kong, and China where business hours extend beyond midnight, such as broadcast television production and scheduling.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The GTFS public transport schedule listings file format has the concept of service days and expects times beyond 24:00 for trips that run after midnight.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] For example, Microsoft Windows and macOS activate the 12-hour notation by default only if a computer is in a handful of specific language and region settings.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The 24-hour system is commonly used in text-based interfaces.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] POSIX programs such as `ls` default to displaying timestamps in 24-hour format.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In the United States (a country which uses 12-hour clocks), the 24-hour clock is often referred to as *military time*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] There is, however, a more specific standard for military time which refines the acceptable written and spoken forms of times on the 24-hour clock.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The first mechanical public clocks introduced in Italy were mechanical 24-hour clocks which counted the 24 hours of the day from one-half hour after sunset to the evening of the following day.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The 24th hour was the last hour of day time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The modern 24-hour system is a late-19th century adaptation of the German midnight-starting system, and then prevailed in the world with the exception of some Anglophone countries.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Striking clocks had to produce 300 strokes each day, which required a lot of rope, and wore out the mechanism quickly, so some localities switched to ringing sequences of 1 to 12 twice, or 1 to 6 repeated four times.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Sandford Fleming, the engineer-in-chief of the Canadian Intercolonial Railway, was an early proponent of using the 24-hour clock as part of a programme to reform timekeeping, which also included establishing time zones and a standard prime meridian.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The Canadian Pacific Railway was among the first organisations to adopt the 24-hour clock, at midsummer 1886.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] A report by a government committee in the United Kingdom noted Italy as the first country among those mentioned to adopt 24-hour time nationally, in 1893.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Other European countries followed: France adopted it in 1912 (the French army in 1909), followed by Denmark (1916), and Greece (1917).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] By 1920, Spain, Portugal, Belgium, and Switzerland had switched, followed by Turkey (1925), and Germany (1927).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] By the early 1920s, many countries in Latin America had also adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] Some of the railways in India had switched before the outbreak of the war.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] During World War I, the British Royal Navy adopted the 24-hour clock in 1915, and the Allied armed forces followed soon after, with the British Army switching officially in 1918.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The Canadian armed forces first started to use the 24-hour clock in late 1917.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In 1920, the United States Navy was the first United States organisation to adopt the system; the United States Army, however, did not officially adopt the 24-hour clock until 1 July 1942.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The use of the 24-hour clock in the United Kingdom has grown steadily since the beginning of the 20th century, although attempts to make the system official failed more than once.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In 1934, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) switched to the 24-hour clock for broadcast announcements and programme listings.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] The experiment was halted after five months following a lack of enthusiasm from the public, and the BBC continued using the 12-hour clock.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In the same year, Pan American World Airways Corporation and Western Airlines in the United States both adopted the 24-hour clock.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] In modern times, the BBC uses a mixture of both the 12-hour and the 24-hour clock.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] British Rail, London Transport, and the London Underground switched to the 24-hour clock for timetables in 1964.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/24-hour-clock] A mixture of the 12- and 24-hour clocks similarly prevails in other English-speaking Commonwealth countries: French speakers have adopted the 24-hour clock in Canada much more broadly than English speakers, and Australia as well as New Zealand also use both systems.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] In metaphysics, the **A series** and the **B series** are two different descriptions of the temporal ordering relation among events.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] The two series differ principally in their use of tense to describe the temporal relation between events and the resulting ontological implications regarding time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] John McTaggart introduced these terms in 1908, in an argument for the unreality of time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] They are now commonly used by contemporary philosophers of time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Metaphysical debate about temporal orderings reaches back to the ancient Greek philosophers Heraclitus and Parmenides.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Parmenides thought that reality is timeless and unchanging.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Heraclitus, in contrast, believed that the world is a process of ceaseless change, flux and decay.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Reality for Heraclitus is dynamic and ephemeral, in a state of constant flux, as in his famous statement that it is impossible to step twice into the same river (since the river is flowing).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] McTaggart distinguished the ancient conceptions as a set of relations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] According to McTaggart, there are two distinct modes in which all events can be ordered in time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] In the first mode (the A series of temporal positions), events are ordered as future, present, and past.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Futurity and pastness allow for degrees, while the present does not.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] When we speak of time in this way, we are speaking in terms of a series of positions which run from the remote past through the recent past to the present, and from the present through the near future all the way to the remote future.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] The essential characteristic of this descriptive modality is **McTaggartian change**: the continual transformation of an event's position within the series of temporal positions, whereby the event is first future, then present, and then past.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] In this sense, change is understood as temporal passage itself, through which events acquire and lose the determinations of futurity, presentness, and pastness.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Moreover, assertions made according to this modality correspond to the temporal perspective of the person who utters them.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] This is the A series of temporal positions.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Although originally McTaggart defined tenses as relational qualities, i.e., qualities that events possess by standing in a certain relation to something outside of time (that does not change its position in time), today it is popularly believed that he treated tenses as monadic properties.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Later philosophers have independently inferred that McTaggart must have understood tense as monadic because English tenses are normally expressed by the non-relational singular predicates "is past", "is present" and "is future", as noted by R.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] An important difference between the two series is that while events continuously change their position in the A series, their position in the B series does not.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] If an event is ever earlier than some events and later than the rest, it is always earlier than and later than those very events.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Furthermore, while events acquire their A-series determinations through a relation to something outside of time, their B-series determinations hold between the events that constitute the B series.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] This is the B series, and the philosophy that says all truths about time can be reduced to B series statements is the B-theory of time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] The logic and the linguistic expression of the two series are radically different.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] The A series is *tensed* and the B series is *tenseless*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] For example, the assertion "it is raining here today" is a tensed assertion because it depends on the temporal perspective—the present—of the person who utters it, while the assertion "It rained here on 29 June 2026" is tenseless because it does not so depend.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] From the point of view of their truth-values, the two propositions are identical (both true or both false) if the first assertion is made on 29 June 2026.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] The non-temporal relation of precedence between two events, say "E precedes F", does not change over time (excluding from this discussion the issue of the relativity of temporal order of causally disconnected events in the theory of relativity).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] On the other hand, the character of being "past, present or future" of the events "E" or "F" does change with time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] In the image of McTaggart the passage of time consists in the fact that terms ever further in the future pass into the present...or that the present advances toward terms ever farther in the future.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the first point of view, we speak as if the B series slides along a fixed A series.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] If we assume the second point of view, we speak as if the A series slides along a fixed B series.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] There are two principal varieties of the A-theory, presentism and the growing block universe.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Both assume an objective present, but presentism assumes that only present objects exist, while the growing block universe assumes both present and past objects exist, but not future ones.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Views that assume no objective present and are therefore versions of the B-theory include eternalism and four-dimensionalism.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] Vincent Conitzer argues that A-theory is related to Benj Hellie's vertiginous question and Caspar Hare's ideas of egocentric presentism and perspectival realism.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/a-series-and-b-series] He argues that A-theory being true and "now" being metaphysically distinguished from other moments of time implies that the "I" is also metaphysically distinguished from other first-person perspectives.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In mathematics, an **abelian group**,[note 1] also called a **commutative group**, is a group in which the result of applying the group operation to two group elements does not depend on the order in which they are written.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] That is, the group operation is commutative.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] With addition as an operation, the integers and the real numbers form abelian groups, and the concept of an abelian group may be viewed as a generalization of these examples.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Abelian groups are named after the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The concept of an abelian group underlies many fundamental algebraic structures, such as fields, rings, vector spaces, and algebras.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The theory of abelian groups is generally simpler than that of their non-abelian counterparts, and finite abelian groups are very well understood and fully classified.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] An abelian group is a set A , together with an operation ･ , that combines any two elements a and b of A to form another element of $A,$ denoted $a\cdot b$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The symbol ･ is a general placeholder for a concretely given operation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Some authors further include as requirements some properties that belong to the definition of an operation: that the operation is *defined* for any ordered pair of elements of A, that the result is *well-defined*, and that the result *belongs to* A.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] A group in which the group operation is not commutative is called a *non-abelian group* or *non-commutative group*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] There are two main notational conventions for abelian groups – additive and multiplicative.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Generally, the multiplicative notation is the usual notation for groups, while the additive notation is the usual notation for modules and rings.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The additive notation may also be used to emphasize that a particular group is abelian, whenever both abelian and non-abelian groups are considered, with some notable exceptions being near-rings and partially ordered groups, where an operation is written additively even when non-abelian.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] To verify that a finite group is abelian, a table (matrix) – known as a Cayley table – can be constructed in a similar fashion to a multiplication table.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] If the group is $G=\{g_{1}=e,g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}\}$ under the operation $\cdot$ , the $(i,j)$ -th entry of this table contains the product $g_{i}\cdot g_{j}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The group is abelian if and only if this table is symmetric about the main diagonal, which means that for all $i,j=1,...,n$ , the $(i,j)$ entry of the table equals the $(j,i)$ entry.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In general, matrices, even invertible matrices, do not form an abelian group under multiplication because matrix multiplication is generally not commutative.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] However, some groups of matrices are abelian groups under matrix multiplication – one example is the group of $2\times 2$ rotation matrices.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Camille Jordan named abelian groups after the Norwegian mathematician Niels Henrik Abel, who had found that the commutativity of the group of a polynomial implies that the roots of the polynomial can be calculated by using radicals.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] If n is a natural number and x is an element of an abelian group G written additively, then $nx$ can be defined as $x+x+\cdots +x$ ( n summands) and $(-n)x=-(nx)$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In this way, G becomes a module over the ring $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In fact, the modules over $\mathbb {Z}$ can be identified with the abelian groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Theorems about abelian groups (i.e. modules over the principal ideal domain $\mathbb {Z}$ ) can often be generalized to theorems about modules over an arbitrary principal ideal domain.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] A typical example is the classification of finitely generated abelian groups which is a specialization of the structure theorem for finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In the case of finitely generated abelian groups, this theorem guarantees that an abelian group splits as a direct sum of a torsion group and a free abelian group.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The former may be written as a direct sum of finitely many groups of the form $\mathbb {Z} /p^{k}\mathbb {Z}$ for p prime, and the latter is a direct sum of finitely many copies of $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] If $f,g:G\to H$ are two group homomorphisms between abelian groups, then their sum $f+g$ , defined by $(f+g)(x)=f(x)+g(x)$ , is again a homomorphism.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] (This is not true if H is a non-abelian group.) The set ${\text{Hom}}(G,H)$ of all group homomorphisms from G to H is therefore an abelian group in its own right.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Somewhat akin to the dimension of vector spaces, every abelian group has a *rank*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] It is defined as the maximal cardinality of a set of linearly independent (over the integers) elements of the group.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Finite abelian groups and torsion groups have rank zero, and every abelian group of rank zero is a torsion group.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The integers and the rational numbers have rank one, as well as every nonzero additive subgroup of the rationals.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] On the other hand, the multiplicative group of the nonzero rationals has an infinite rank, as it is a free abelian group with the set of the prime numbers as a basis (this results from the fundamental theorem of arithmetic).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The center $Z(G)$ of a group G is the set of elements that commute with every element of G .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] A group G is abelian if and only if it is equal to its center $Z(G)$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The center of a group G is always a characteristic abelian subgroup of G .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] If the quotient group $G/Z(G)$ of a group by its center is cyclic then G is abelian.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Cyclic groups of integers modulo n , $\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z}$ , were among the first examples of groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] It turns out that an arbitrary finite abelian group is isomorphic to a direct sum of finite cyclic groups of prime power order, and these orders are uniquely determined, forming a complete system of invariants.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The automorphism group of a finite abelian group can be described directly in terms of these invariants.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The theory had been first developed in the 1879 paper of Georg Frobenius and Ludwig Stickelberger and later was both simplified and generalized to finitely generated modules over a principal ideal domain, forming an important chapter of linear algebra.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Any group of prime order is isomorphic to a cyclic group and therefore abelian.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Any group whose order is a square of a prime number is also abelian.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In fact, for every prime number p there are (up to isomorphism) exactly two groups of order $p^{2}$ , namely $\mathbb {Z} _{p^{2}}$ and $\mathbb {Z} _{p}\times \mathbb {Z} _{p}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The **fundamental theorem of finite abelian groups** states that every finite abelian group G can be expressed as the direct sum of cyclic subgroups of prime-power order; it is also known as the **basis theorem for finite abelian groups**.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Moreover, automorphism groups of cyclic groups are examples of abelian groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] This is generalized by the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups, with finite groups being the special case when *G* has zero rank; this in turn admits numerous further generalizations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The classification was proven by Leopold Kronecker in 1870, though it was not stated in modern group-theoretic terms until later, and was preceded by a similar classification of quadratic forms by Carl Friedrich Gauss in 1801; see history for details.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The cyclic group $\mathbb {Z} _{mn}$ of order $mn$ is isomorphic to the direct sum of $\mathbb {Z} _{m}$ and $\mathbb {Z} _{n}$ if and only if m and n are coprime.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The same can be said for any abelian group of order 15, leading to the remarkable conclusion that all abelian groups of order 15 are isomorphic.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] See also list of small groups for finite abelian groups of order 30 or less.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] One can apply the fundamental theorem to count (and sometimes determine) the automorphisms of a given finite abelian group G .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Given this, the fundamental theorem shows that to compute the automorphism group of G it suffices to compute the automorphism groups of the Sylow p -subgroups separately (that is, all direct sums of cyclic subgroups, each with order a power of p ).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] One special case is when $n=1$ , so that there is only one cyclic prime-power factor in the Sylow p -subgroup P .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In this case the theory of automorphisms of a finite cyclic group can be used.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Another special case is when n is arbitrary but $e_{i}=1$ for $1\leq i\leq n$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] so elements of this subgroup can be viewed as comprising a vector space of dimension n over the finite field of p elements $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] where $\mathrm {GL}$ is the appropriate general linear group.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In the most general case, where the $e_{i}$ and n are arbitrary, the automorphism group is more difficult to determine.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] One can check that this yields the orders in the previous examples as special cases (see Hillar & Rhea).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] An abelian group A is finitely generated if it contains a finite set of elements (called *generators*) $G=\{x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}\}$ such that every element of the group is a linear combination with integer coefficients of elements of G.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] This homomorphism is surjective, and its kernel is finitely generated (since integers form a Noetherian ring).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Consider the matrix M with integer entries, such that the entries of its jth column are the coefficients of the jth generator of the kernel.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Then, the abelian group is isomorphic to the cokernel of linear map defined by M.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Conversely every integer matrix defines a finitely generated abelian group.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] It follows that the study of finitely generated abelian groups is totally equivalent with the study of integer matrices.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In particular, changing the generating set of A is equivalent with multiplying M on the left by a unimodular matrix (that is, an invertible integer matrix whose inverse is also an integer matrix).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Changing the generating set of the kernel of M is equivalent with multiplying M on the right by a unimodular matrix.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] where U and V are unimodular, and S is a matrix such that all non-diagonal entries are zero, the non-zero diagonal entries ⁠ $d_{1,1},\ldots ,d_{k,k}$ ⁠ are the first ones, and ⁠ $d_{j,j}$ ⁠ is a divisor of ⁠ $d_{i,i}$ ⁠ for *i* > *j*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] where r is the number of zero rows at the bottom of S (and also the rank of the group).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] This is the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The existence of algorithms for Smith normal form shows that the fundamental theorem of finitely generated abelian groups is not only a theorem of abstract existence, but provides a way for computing expression of finitely generated abelian groups as direct sums.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The simplest infinite abelian group is the infinite cyclic group $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Any finitely generated abelian group A is isomorphic to the direct sum of r copies of $\mathbb {Z}$ and a finite abelian group, which in turn is decomposable into a direct sum of finitely many cyclic groups of prime power orders.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Even though the decomposition is not unique, the number r , called the rank of A , and the prime powers giving the orders of finite cyclic summands are uniquely determined.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] By contrast, classification of general infinitely generated abelian groups is far from complete.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Divisible groups, i.e. abelian groups A in which the equation $nx=a$ admits a solution $x\in A$ for any natural number n and element a of A , constitute one important class of infinite abelian groups that can be completely characterized.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Every divisible group is isomorphic to a direct sum, with summands isomorphic to $\mathbb {Q}$ and Prüfer groups $\mathbb {Q} _{p}/\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ for various prime numbers p , and the cardinality of the set of summands of each type is uniquely determined.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Moreover, if a divisible group A is a subgroup of an abelian group G then A admits a direct complement: a subgroup C of G such that $G=A\oplus C$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Thus divisible groups are injective modules in the category of abelian groups, and conversely, every injective abelian group is divisible (Baer's criterion).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] An abelian group without non-zero divisible subgroups is called **reduced**.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Two important special classes of infinite abelian groups with diametrically opposite properties are *torsion groups* and *torsion-free groups*, exemplified by the groups $\mathbb {Q} /\mathbb {Z}$ (periodic) and $\mathbb {Q}$ (torsion-free).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] An abelian group is called **periodic** or **torsion**, if every element has finite order.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] A direct sum of finite cyclic groups is periodic.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Although the converse statement is not true in general, some special cases are known.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The first and second Prüfer theorems state that if A is a periodic group, and it either has a **bounded exponent**, i.e., $nA=0$ for some natural number n , or is countable and the p -heights of the elements of A are finite for each p , then A is isomorphic to a direct sum of finite cyclic groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The cardinality of the set of direct summands isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z} /p^{m}\mathbb {Z}$ in such a decomposition is an invariant of A .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] These theorems were later subsumed in the **Kulikov criterion**.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] In a different direction, Helmut Ulm found an extension of the second Prüfer theorem to countable abelian p -groups with elements of infinite height: those groups are completely classified by means of their Ulm invariants.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] An abelian group is called **torsion-free** if every non-zero element has infinite order.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] An abelian group that is neither periodic nor torsion-free is called **mixed**.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] If A is an abelian group and $T(A)$ is its torsion subgroup, then the factor group $A/T(A)$ is torsion-free.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] However, in general the torsion subgroup is not a direct summand of A , so A is *not* isomorphic to $T(A)\oplus A/T(A)$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Thus the theory of mixed groups involves more than simply combining the results about periodic and torsion-free groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The additive group $\mathbb {Z}$ of integers is torsion-free $\mathbb {Z}$ -module.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] One of the most basic invariants of an infinite abelian group A is its rank: the cardinality of the maximal linearly independent subset of A .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Abelian groups of rank 0 are precisely the periodic groups, while torsion-free abelian groups of rank 1 are necessarily subgroups of $\mathbb {Q}$ and can be completely described.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] More generally, a torsion-free abelian group of finite rank r is a subgroup of $\mathbb {Q} _{r}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] On the other hand, the group of p -adic integers $\mathbb {Z} _{p}$ is a torsion-free abelian group of infinite $\mathbb {Z}$ -rank and the groups $\mathbb {Z} _{p}^{n}$ with different n are non-isomorphic, so this invariant does not even fully capture properties of some familiar groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The classification theorems for finitely generated, divisible, countable periodic, and rank 1 torsion-free abelian groups explained above were all obtained before 1950 and form a foundation of the classification of more general infinite abelian groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Important technical tools used in classification of infinite abelian groups are pure and basic subgroups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Introduction of various invariants of torsion-free abelian groups has been one avenue of further progress.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] See the books by Irving Kaplansky, László Fuchs, Phillip Griffith, and David Arnold, as well as the proceedings of the conferences on Abelian Group Theory published in *Lecture Notes in Mathematics* for more recent findings.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The additive group of a ring is an abelian group, but not all abelian groups are additive groups of rings (with nontrivial multiplication).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Many large abelian groups possess a natural topology, which turns them into topological groups.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] The collection of all abelian groups, together with the homomorphisms between them, forms the category ${\textbf {Ab}}$ , the prototype of an abelian category.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Wanda Szmielew (1955) proved that the first-order theory of abelian groups, unlike its non-abelian counterpart, is decidable.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Most algebraic structures other than Boolean algebras are undecidable.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Moreover, abelian groups of infinite order lead, quite surprisingly, to deep questions about the set theory commonly assumed to underlie all of mathematics.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/abelian-group] Take the Whitehead problem: are all Whitehead groups of infinite order also free abelian groups?
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The **Arnowitt–Deser–Misner** (**ADM**) **formalism** (named for its authors Richard Arnowitt, Stanley Deser and Charles W.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Misner) is a Hamiltonian formulation of general relativity that plays an important role in canonical quantum gravity and numerical relativity.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The comprehensive review of the formalism that the authors published in 1962 has been reprinted in the journal *General Relativity and Gravitation*, while the original papers can be found in the archives of *Physical Review*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The formalism supposes that spacetime is foliated into a family of spacelike surfaces ⁠ $\Sigma _{t}$ ⁠, labeled by their time coordinate ⁠ t ⁠, and with coordinates on each slice given by ⁠ $x^{i}$ ⁠.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The dynamic variables of this theory are taken to be the metric tensor of three-dimensional spatial slices ⁠ $\gamma _{ij}(t,x^{k})$ ⁠ and their conjugate momenta ⁠ $\pi ^{ij}(t,x^{k})$ ⁠.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Using these variables it is possible to define a Hamiltonian, and thereby write the equations of motion for general relativity in the form of Hamilton's equations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] In addition to the twelve variables ⁠ $\gamma _{ij}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\pi ^{ij}$ ⁠, there are four Lagrange multipliers: the lapse function, ⁠ N ⁠, and components of shift vector field, ⁠ $N_{i}$ ⁠.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] These describe how each of the "leaves" ⁠ $\Sigma _{t}$ ⁠ of the foliation of spacetime are welded together.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The equations of motion for these variables can be freely specified; this freedom corresponds to the freedom to specify how to lay out the coordinate system in space and time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Most references adopt notation in which four dimensional tensors are written in abstract index notation, and that Greek indices are spacetime indices taking values (0, 1, 2, 3) and Latin indices are spatial indices taking values (1, 2, 3).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] In the derivation here, a superscript (4) is prepended to quantities that typically have both a three-dimensional and a four-dimensional version, such as the metric tensor for three-dimensional slices $g_{ij}$ and the metric tensor for the full four-dimensional spacetime ${^{(4)}}g_{\mu \nu }$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The text here uses Einstein notation in which summation over repeated indices is assumed.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Two types of derivatives are used: Partial derivatives are denoted either by the operator $\partial _{i}$ or by subscripts preceded by a comma.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Covariant derivatives are denoted either by the operator $\nabla _{i}$ or by subscripts preceded by a semicolon.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The absolute value of the determinant of the matrix of metric tensor coefficients is represented by g (with no indices).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Other tensor symbols written without indices represent the trace of the corresponding tensor such as $\pi =g^{ij}\pi _{ij}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The **ADM split** denotes the separation of the spacetime metric into three spatial components and one temporal component (foliation).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The basic idea is to express the spacetime metric in terms of a lapse function that represents the time evolution between hypersurfaces, and a shift vector that represents spatial coordinate changes between these hypersurfaces) along with a 3D spatial metric.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] where N is the lapse function encoding the proper time evolution, $N_{i}$ is the shift vector, encoding how spatial coordinates change between hypersurfaces. $g_{ij}$ is the emergent 3D spatial metric on each hypersurface.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] This decomposition allows for a separation of the spacetime evolution equations into constraints (which relate the initial data on a spatial hypersurface) and evolution equations (which describe how the geometry of spacetime changes from one hypersurface to another).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] which is a product of the square root of the determinant of the four-dimensional metric tensor for the full spacetime and its Ricci scalar.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] This is the Lagrangian from the Einstein–Hilbert action.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The desired outcome of the derivation is to define an embedding of three-dimensional spatial slices in the four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] will be the generalized coordinates for a Hamiltonian formulation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] using standard techniques and definitions.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The symbols ${^{(4)}}\Gamma _{ij}^{0}$ are Christoffel symbols associated with the metric of the full four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] are the remaining elements of the four-metric tensor.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Having identified the quantities for the formulation, the next step is to rewrite the Lagrangian in terms of these variables.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] which are known as the Hamiltonian constraint and the momentum constraint respectively.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The lapse and the shift appear in the Lagrangian as Lagrange multipliers.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] is a non-linear set of partial differential equations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] and the lapse and shift themselves can be freely specified, reflecting the fact that coordinate systems can be freely specified in both space and time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Using the ADM formulation, it is possible to attempt to construct a quantum theory of gravity in the same way that one constructs the Schrödinger equation corresponding to a given Hamiltonian in quantum mechanics.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] More precisely, the replacing of classical variables by operators is restricted by commutation relations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The hats represent operators in quantum theory.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] This leads to the Wheeler–DeWitt equation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] There are relatively few known exact solutions to the Einstein field equations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] In order to find other solutions, there is an active field of study known as numerical relativity in which supercomputers are used to find approximate solutions to the equations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] In order to construct such solutions numerically, most researchers start with a formulation of the Einstein equations closely related to the ADM formulation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The most common approaches start with an initial value problem based on the ADM formalism.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] In Hamiltonian formulations, the basic point is replacement of set of second order equations by another first order set of equations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] We may get this second set of equations by Hamiltonian formulation in an easy way.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Of course this is very useful for numerical physics, because reducing the order of differential equations is often convenient if we want to prepare equations for a computer.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] ADM energy is a special way to define the energy in general relativity, which is only applicable to some special geometries of spacetime that asymptotically approach a well-defined metric tensor at infinity – for example a spacetime that asymptotically approaches Minkowski space.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] The ADM energy in these cases is defined as a function of the deviation of the metric tensor from its prescribed asymptotic form.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] In other words, the ADM energy is computed as the strength of the gravitational field at infinity.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] If the required asymptotic form is time-independent (such as the Minkowski space itself), then it respects the time-translational symmetry.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Noether's theorem then implies that the ADM energy is conserved.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] According to general relativity, the conservation law for the total energy does not hold in more general, time-dependent backgrounds – for example, it is completely violated in physical cosmology.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] Cosmic inflation in particular is able to produce energy (and mass) from "nothing" because the vacuum energy density is roughly constant, but the volume of the Universe grows exponentially.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/adm-formalism] By using the ADM decomposition and introducing extra auxiliary fields, in 2009 Deruelle et al. found a method to find the Gibbons–Hawking–York boundary term for modified gravity theories "whose Lagrangian is an arbitrary function of the Riemann tensor".
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] There are many symmetries in nature besides time translation, such as spatial translation or rotational symmetries.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] These symmetries can be broken and explain diverse phenomena such as crystals, superconductivity, and the Higgs mechanism.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] However, it was thought until very recently that time-translation symmetry could not be broken.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Time crystals, a state of matter first observed in 2017, break time-translation symmetry.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Symmetries are of prime importance in physics and are closely related to the hypothesis that certain physical quantities are only relative and unobservable.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Symmetries apply to the equations that govern the physical laws (e.g. to a Hamiltonian or Lagrangian) rather than the initial conditions, values or magnitudes of the equations themselves and state that the laws remain unchanged under a transformation.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] If a symmetry is preserved under a transformation it is said to be *invariant*.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Symmetries in nature lead directly to conservation laws, something which is precisely formulated by Noether's theorem.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] To formally describe time-translation symmetry we say the equations, or laws, that describe a system at times t and $t+\tau$ are the same for any value of t and $\tau$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Of course, this quantity describes the total energy whose conservation is due to the time-translation invariance of the equation of motion.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] By studying the composition of symmetry transformations, e.g. of geometric objects, one reaches the conclusion that they form a group and, more specifically, a Lie transformation group if one considers continuous, finite symmetry transformations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Different symmetries form different groups with different geometries.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Time independent Hamiltonian systems form a group of time translations that is described by the non-compact, abelian, Lie group $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] TTS is therefore a dynamical or Hamiltonian dependent symmetry rather than a kinematical symmetry which would be the same for the entire set of Hamiltonians at issue.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Other examples can be seen in the study of time evolution equations of classical and quantum physics.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Many differential equations describing time evolution equations are expressions of invariants associated to some Lie group and the theory of these groups provides a unifying viewpoint for the study of all special functions and all their properties.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] In fact, Sophus Lie invented the theory of Lie groups when studying the symmetries of differential equations.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] The integration of a (partial) differential equation by the method of separation of variables or by Lie algebraic methods is intimately connected with the existence of symmetries.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] For example, the exact solubility of the Schrödinger equation in quantum mechanics can be traced back to the underlying invariances.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] In the latter case, the investigation of symmetries allows for an interpretation of the degeneracies, where different configurations to have the same energy, which generally occur in the energy spectrum of quantum systems.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] The invariance of a Hamiltonian ${\hat {H}}$ of an isolated system under time translation implies its energy does not change with the passage of time.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Conservation of energy implies, according to the Heisenberg equations of motion, that $[{\hat {H}},{\hat {H}}]=0$ .
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Where ${\hat {T}}(t)=e^{i{\hat {H}}t/\hbar }$ is the time-translation operator which implies invariance of the Hamiltonian under the time-translation operation and leads to the conservation of energy.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] In many nonlinear field theories like general relativity or Yang–Mills theories, the basic field equations are highly nonlinear and exact solutions are only known for 'sufficiently symmetric' distributions of matter (e.g. rotationally or axially symmetric configurations).
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Time-translation symmetry is guaranteed only in spacetimes where the metric is static: that is, where there is a coordinate system in which the metric coefficients contain no time variable.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Many general relativity systems are not static in any frame of reference so no conserved energy can be defined.
[src:time-translation-symmetry/time-translation-symmetry] Time crystals, a state of matter first observed in 2017, break discrete time-translation symmetry.
